<% content_for :title, "erbswap — async UX for Rails without growing your own framework" %>

<section class="hero">
  <h2>Server-driven UI for Rails, without a framework.</h2>
  <p class="lead">
    <strong>erbswap</strong> is a thin pattern: a Rails controller concern and just under 200 lines of vanilla JS.
    Your server renders plain ERB partials. The browser does <code>fetch</code> + DOM swap. That's the whole thing.
  </p>
  <p>
    Zero dependencies. Zero build step. No <code>npm</code>, no <code>hx-*</code> attributes,
    no <code>&lt;turbo-frame&gt;</code> custom element. The point isn't to compete with HTMX or
    Turbo &mdash; it's to give you a deliberately limited starting point with a clear
    upgrade path the moment you outgrow it.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="examples">
  <h3>Try the examples</h3>
  <ul class="example-list">
    <li>
      <h4><%= link_to "Example 1 — Modal + form swap", examples_tasks_path %></h4>
      <p>
        Pattern A (form-driven swap) + Pattern B (opener-driven fresh fetch) combined.
        Open the modal &rarr; run a task &rarr; the result swaps in place. Demonstrates
        the canonical <em>same-frame-id wrapper across every state</em> invariant.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h4><%= link_to "Example 2 — Inline form validation", examples_new_signup_path %></h4>
      <p>
        A signup form where username availability is checked via async swap before final submit.
        Demonstrates partial swap without a modal &mdash; pure inline interaction.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <h4><%= link_to "Example 3 — Click-to-load", examples_articles_path %></h4>
      <p>
        A list of articles where clicking &ldquo;Show preview&rdquo; fetches and swaps a
        preview block in place. Demonstrates the <code>data-erbswap-action="load"</code>
        click trigger.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="invariants">
  <h3>The four invariants</h3>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Same frame id, every state.</strong> The wrapper <code>&lt;div id="..."&gt;</code> is identical across initial/success/empty/error partials.</li>
    <li><strong>Two swap modes only.</strong> <code>innerHTML</code> and <code>replace</code>. No <code>beforeend</code>, no positional swap.</li>
    <li><strong>Single controller entry point.</strong> <code>render_erbswap(partial:, locals:, status:)</code>. No second helper.</li>
    <li><strong>Out of scope.</strong> Out-of-band swap, history push, SSE, retry, abort. When you need these, move to HTMX or Turbo.</li>
  </ol>
  <p class="invariants__note">
    The discipline is the value. Without these ceilings, this library would grow into a 1000-line
    home-built framework &mdash; the exact NIH trap it exists to avoid.
  </p>
</section>
